<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Ents of Fangorn: Dissected<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.91)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7058'>Jonathan "Carny" brown</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7058&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 20, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> first off, I have put HTML in here because I seem to remember my last article clumping together. I hope it doesn&#39;t look stupid, as this is my first &quot;real&quot; article.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Greetings!<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
I have been itching to write an article for a while now, and I had no idea what I could <br />
Possibly write about that would be useful and that had not been written before. I noticed that no one has done a full review of all of the new Ents of Fangorn cards. I have seen people try to do these before, but they always seem to get bored halfway through and the article sucks. I decree that this day I will not stop until I have given at least a semi-intelligent synopsis of the possible uses for EVERY SINGLE CARD in the expansion. Bear in mind that all these snippets are purely my own opinion and are intended based on the Standard environment. I may make some comments about Towers, but Open format is dead to me.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
I guess I’ll start off with overall observations. I feel like this will be a very frustrating set to play with. Not because the cards aren’t good, or they aren’t interesting. Quite the opposite. I fell that many of these cards are going to make me think about how to use them the best, and gosh darnit, that sucks. Nah, just kidding. Basically what I mean is that a lot of the cards are very obviously powerful, but have some drawback(like Gandalf or the new Aragorn) that makes you go out of your way to use them. Whether this is a good thing or not remains to be seen.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
I am going to type the name of the card, but I won’t have time to type up all of the text etc. of the card, so you’ll just have to open another window and look at the pdf. On Decipher. Wah. This is going to take enough time as it is, so gimme a break!<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Dunland – for this first time, we get some Dunland cards that don’t do anything unless you control multiple sites. These 2 new cards seem quite balanced. The new Common-Hides, as it’s been called, is less than impressive and we get some dirt cheap skirmish phasers and automatic site control.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Bound by Rage – now, this is decipher’s idea of a non-rare Hides. Yes, it does SORT OF the same thing, but is it a replacement? No. I can see myself finding room for one copy of this card in my Dunland deck, but the fact that you essentially need 9 pool (3 for the card and 3 each for 2 minions) to get the full effect out of the card limits its utility. Also, it loses the best part about Hides, namely being a possession. One of Dunland’s strengths is that the do not rely on conditions to win the game, and if you are going to rely on this as your wound prevention, then condition removal is going to gang bang you.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Dunlending Elder – this guy has potential. The idea of a 12 strength minion that is fierce and Damage +1 for 2 pool is almost too good to pass up. The problem is that unless you can control 2 sites quickly, this is an awful minion. Dunlend needs to control sites to win the game, but usually they can get going simply by grabbing one site, then snowball from there. I don’t see anyone successfully using more than 1 or 2 of this guy in a deck, simply because if you draw him up before you get 2 sites he’s worse than a Brigand, and if you’re only going to play 1 or 2, why play any? This guy is gong to give me migraines. I think he’ll be huge in combination with Ready to Fall.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Dunlending Footman / Reserve – these guys are both essentially the same. They both drop for cheaper during the skirmish the phase. The neat thing is that if you consider that you’re going to be playing them with a Mob or an Arsonist, they will cost you 1 and 0 respectively. The thing is, while the Footman would initially seem better, since he’s bigger and has vitality 2, but the beauty of the reserve is that he’s going to get played for free during the skirmish phase. This is HUGE. I don’t think I need to tell you why. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Dunlending Headman – when I was told what this guy does,  my friend neglected to mention that your opponent could discard 2 cards to stop you from controlling a site. Now, I don’t know about you, but in my opinion, the only this guy is going to control a site is when your opponent doesn’t have any cards in their hand. What opponent would rather keep two cards(ANY cards) than stop you from controlling a site. Especially when they know that Dunlend relies on controlling sites to win games. The only way this guy is going to control you any sites, is if you play him in multiples. And if that happens…..huge. I think this guy is going to see a lot of play, whether that means he’s good or not will remain to be seen. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Hill Clan – big. Mean. Not really all that good. While this guy has the potential to overwhelm some people, the fact that he costs 8 pool means that he will make your minions that turn(if you get anymore out) VERY vulnerable to wounding. Against decks that give you lots of pool, the extra minion he plays will almost always be inconsequential. Against decks running a smaller fellowship, they will either deny the pool to play him and another minion or simply kill him with archery/defend it and hope. I think he’ll see lots of play in Towers and he’ll be a monster in Sealed and Draft play, but I don’t see much of a future for the Hill Clan in Standard.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Ready to Fall – this card has problems, and it’s one of the ones that will make you think about how to play it. Since it doesn’t require you to control sites to play it, it’ll be easy to play it, but the question is: do you play this AND Constantly Threatening, or do you use one or the other? If this card gets working, Constantly Threatening is useless. On the other hand, what if you never control 2 sites, then you have no recursion of your nasty minions. I expect to see new Dunland decks concentrating purely on controlling those 2 sites and abusing this card and the Elder. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Too Long Have These Peasants Stood – Saruman’s Power for Dunland. Almost. Saruman;s Power is quite possibly the best Shadow card in any format, and now Dunland gets it’s own version with one important drawback. You need to win a skirmish first. This means two things. First, you’ll have to win a skirmish, which means they get to use Help, Trust, Promises etc. to try and prevent you from playing this card. This is a big the deal, because that’s the beauty of Saruman;s Power since it can remove all those annoying conditions before you fight, making winning a fight all that much simpler. The second problem is that you cannot “Power” and then play your conditions, you’ll have to hold onto those No Retreats, Over the Isens. Etc. and play them the next turn, which can suck. This is a good card, but no replacement for the Power of ol’ crusty.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Dwarves – the dwarves get 3 new cards, not really enough to introduce a new strategy. If I say too much right here, the rest of the dwarf stuff will be useless.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Lend us Your Aid  - now, I gotta tell ya, this card is really cool. Lets assume you started Arwen and Gimli and used the site to pull Legolas. You also have out, lets say, a Naith Warband(we’ll get to him later). With this card you get, for 2 exertions and zero pool, companions at strength 12, 9, 9 and 9 with ZERO possessions. This is cool. It’s weak to Palantir, and it’s not going to be usable twice per turn without shoulder to shoulder, but I see much usability in this card. GO Gimli.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Suspended Palaces – I guess the idea here is to use this card to get Toss Me stacked on a condition. I honestly think there are better ways, and otherwise this card does almost nothing. There are ways to use it, but they involve sub-par cards to begin with and aren’t worth all of the card slots/ pool to use. I am glad Decipher tried to ramp up the Dwarf card stacking, but the randomness of it makes all the cards, not just this one, less than useful. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Toss Me – hilarious card, and one that HAD to be made. Incidentally, this is not an awful card. It has potential to make Gimli a monster fighter. Lockbearer w/ Bracers and Battle Axe is an 11(assuming you’ve got 2 Hobbits). 4 copies of Toss Me makes him a 15 which beats the Witch King. Now, back to reality, the set-up it takes to get this happening is insanely complicated and all gets wiped out by any condition removal. This card has the same problem as My Axe is Notched. Good intentions, potential, but too weak and random to be played in a competitive deck.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Elves – elves get a new strategy called Elven Telepathy. While it remains to be seem whether or not this will be a viable ability, it seems to have potential. With the power to look at the top card(s) of the deck to use the twilight cost to shrink minions, Elves seem to be getting some skirmish power. The biggest weakness, as always, is that Elves really have no incentive to win fights, since they have no Damage Bonuses. Why go through a lot of trouble to win a fight when the minion still won’t die?<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Agility – an elf pumper condition. Not much to say, except that it’s pretty good. 2 pool seems a little much for it, since Rohan has Thundering Host which does ESSENITALLY the same thing, except it’s not unique and has the potential to heal. It seems that they overprice Elf cards on purpose, and that’s what kills the culture. Ahem, enough ranting.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Arwen, Evenstar of Her People – I am not impressed with this version of Arwen. I think the main reason, at least in Standard, is that Daughter of Elrond is just so much better. Nazgul are so strong in Standard that it just doesn’t make since to use an Arwen that needs to cause 3 wounds to tie her against the Nazgul. In Open, I actually see her being usable. Asfaloth and Gwemegil make her a 10 and combined with Galadriel and Elrond to heal a slew of allies, you’ll be able to win every fight you need to and heal all those wounds every turn. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Banner of Elbereth – okay, first of the Banners. If these weren’t hand weapons, they would be AWESOME. The fact that this card can let you draw cards AND liberate sites is just awesome. Unfortunately, you need to win a skirmish to activate either of it’s abilities, and the fact that it is a hand weapon that gives no strength bonus means that unless you’re playing against Moria, you’re NOT going to be winning a whole lot of skirmishes. And if you’re going to put a card in your deck just to draw a card every time your opponent plays a Goblin Runner, then you need more help than I can give.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Elrond, Keeper of Vilya – alright, heres the next best thing to playing with Lord of Rivendel. Used in combination with Forewarned and a means to shuffle your deck, this guy is a card drawing and healing engine unmatched, even by Elrond’s other versions. If decipher clarifies cards like Sam, FC and Sam, FG to prevent you from “searching” for Bill the Pony and Sam’s Pack multiple times in a turn, Elrond will draw a card and heal an Elf EVERY turn. Beware of adding too much pool.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Forearmed – quite a good pumper. Play Nazgul or Trolls for you shadow side, and you’ll get the most out of this card. While it is a bit random, you can use Forewarned to see whats up there. The cool thing is that once you play one of these, the card stays on top and you know what it was. Then, you’ll know whether or not to use Galadriel of the Naith Troop to win the fight. Not a great card, but good in that deck, which could turn out to be better than everyone thought.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Forewarned – alright, this one card is essential to the whole “Elven Telepathy” strategy. Not much to it, if you’re going to try to work the whole elf peeking deck, this card should be in in multiples. If you’re playing anything else, look elsewhere. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Galadriel, Keeper of Nenya – Galadriel is somewhat useful. Again, she is going to see some play simply because she is an ally for Secret Sentinels whose special ability MIGHT get used. In an ET deck, she’ll be a relatively effective pumper in combination with peeking cards like Forewarned and Forearmed. She will also combo well with Sam to set up a sure pump. Too specialized to see a whole lot of play, but great in an ET deck.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Gift of Foresight – yet another peeking card. I think that this one’s a little less effective than Forewarned, but it also has some things up on it’s brethren. The fact that you can take the card into your hand means that this card is effectively “ not there “ in your deck, since as soon as you drawn it, you can draw another one. I would expect to see this card showing up in decks that try for a shadow kill, as they will allow you to set up a shadow hand. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Must be a Dream – another peeker. This one, like Gift, suffers from the fact that it is an event, which means this card will let you peek once. The chance to heal 2 companions is decent, but I would imagine Elrond will see more play. The good thing is that elves do not, as of yet, have effective fellowship phase healing. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Naith Longbow – You asked for, you got it. Decipher gives us the card that will make the Naiths, if not great, somewhat more playable. I am excited that Taurnil can now add to the twilight cost of possessions but be immune to Relentless Charge and other archer hate cards. Also, this and an Elven Sword on Naith Warband makes for a strong fighting companion.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Naith Troop – this guy is pure crap. He is a bit above the curve for your average Elf companion, but you need to spot 3 elves to play him and his game text is pretty awful. Exerting a companion for a slight chance that he’ll win the skirmish is a bad deal in my mind. Especially since there’s no way to make Elves damage +1, this means if you win the fight against a fierce minion, he will most likely come back without any penalty for having lost that first fight. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Naith Warband – now this is more like it. Elves get armor….sort of. The only drawback about the Warband is the fact that you need to spot 3 Elf companions to play him. This is not too bad, though. My main complaint about the Warband is the puny vitality. 9 Strength is very nice, and with Naith Longbow and Elven Sword you’ll have an 11 strength fighter, who can block the new Balrog with very little trouble. The fact that it is unique is a big bummer, but this card gives the Elves a third fighting companion without a silly gimmick.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Gandalf – the Gandalf culture has 2 new strategies. First off is Ents. They are all about being huge and giving out tons of pool. With a couple of events and 2 permanent based pumpers, the only initial weakness seems to be swarms. The new Gandalf oriented cards seem to be Decipher’s attempt at bringing Gandalf back to the fighting realm instead of support, where he has been relegated since Chief Counselor hit the scene. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Boomed and Trumpeted – ahhhh, damage bonuses in an event are always cool. Assuming you’ll usually have both Hobbits in play, this’ll usually be a +2 +2 pump. That’s not REALLY great, but since most Ents are already 10 strength, this is just to push them over the edge. Also, the Damage +2 means they’ll be killing anything short of a major minion. This seems to be an essential card in the Ents’ arsenal.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Crack into Rubble – now this card brings up the most thoughts of all the Ent cards. When Decipher first started spoiling the Ents of Fangorn cards, the question I had was whether of not to play Gandalf with the Ents. This card just about answers the question for me. With Site Liberation and Condition removal in one card that requires only 2 Ents, it seems the Ents have little use for the old gay man. While one condition for 2 wounds is not a great deal, it opens up another companion slot for Ent decks, which means another big fighter who doesn’t need support cards to win skirmishes. Moria is going to be the toughest matchup for Ents, I believe, but being able to nuke Swarms  makes the matchup very winnable.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Enraged – Savagery for Ents. This is how they should have made all the condtions that say discard in regroup, then they would see some play. I just don’t know what else to say about this card, it is like a semi-permanent Skirmish Event.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Ent Avenger – while all the other Ents were out being awesome and laying everything to burnination, this guy was asleep in the crisper drawer. While he is usually going to be an 8, the fact that he starts to fall apart when your fellowship does, and the fact that there are other, much better, Ent companions out there, makes Ent Avenger the weakest of the Leafy Flock.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Ent Horde – wow. 15 twilight? Nah, usually he’s going to cost A LOT less. My theory is that most Ent decks are going to run Treebeard as an ally, which will make this guy possibly as cheap as, well, free! The defender +1 helps to make up for the biggest weakness Ent decks have, which is swarms. This means that a swarm deck is going to have to get AT LEAST 2 more minions than you companions to double up on Frodowski. This guy is money, trust me.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Ent Moot – well, basically a sword for an ent. The downside being that it costs an exertion from a Hobbit to play it, and that it’s a condition. I feel like I need to say more, but there’s really not much to say. I would put this card down as “The Last Alliance of Hobbits and Trees”. It’s a really good card, no more, no less.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Gandalf, Mithrandir – now, here’s the first entry from the Gandalf strategy. Mithrandir is a beast, 10 strength is the highest ever printed on a companion, plus he’s damage +1. This makes him a great fighter to begin with, getting only better with the addition of any possessions you can muster. Obviously, this skirmish wining power can only come at a cost, and cost you this will. Every time you move, Gandalf smokes a pack(or four) of ciggs and takes a wound. This means that by the time you move to site 3, which is a common first turn move, Gandalf will be 2 wounds from a pine box. Lung cancer’s a took. The only way to offset this drawback is to do the obvious and use King in Exile, but this means you’ll need to stop to remove the wound, making double stepping with Mithrandir a sketchy prospect. The best method I can think of for keeping Mithrandir running is some form of Shire Countryside deck that removes burdens during the Skirmish phase and then heals Mithrandir’s walking Bunyans. Head buster.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Glamdring, Lightning Brand – interesting. Gandalf is now able to manhandle ANY minion, which means that when you play those 3 Servants to beat a big giant minion, that minion is going DOWN. Not really going to be all that necessary most of the time, but it’s always nice to have the option. Original is probably more widely useful, but if for some reason you don’t want to use Shadowfax with Mithrandir, this is a better choice since we won’t wanna be exerting bunyan boy. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Host of Fangorn – essentially the same as the Horde, but a slight tookeaper at the expense of 1 vitality and the defender +1 ability. A must play in any Ent deck, and a true beat stick with an Ent Moot onboard.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Quickbeam, Bregalad – okay, first off this guy’s name means “Quickbeam, Quickbeam”. With that out of the way, this fella straight up rocks. He starts with Merry and Pippin giving you a good fighter to start with and some reduction when playing your bigger Ent boys. Not a complicated card, but he’s really usefull in Ent decks, and actually pretty good in NON Ent decks, being that he’s basically Aragorn with 1 less vitality. I could see Dauntless Hunter deck starting him and the 2 Hobbits and pulling Leggs. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Roused – the other Ent pumper, and the more powerful one. The exertion is not too big of a deal, and the potential for +4 from one event makes it even with every other good pumper in skirmish winning ability. Whether this is a needed card, since the Ents have the use of Enraged and Ent Moot, remains to be seem. It will depend on whether or people start to play more giant minions as a response to the abundance of pool given by the Ents.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Skinbark, Fladrif – alright, this guy seems pointless, right? Why play him when you can just play Birchseed and have a better special ability. Well, Skinbark is a lot better than you think. Firt off, usually Skinbark will cost you 4, sometimes as little as free, but I would think on average you’re going to have out Treebeard as an ally, Quickbeam and the two Hobbits. This puts Skinbark at 3 cost, which is actually better than Birchseed, because Birchseed is unhasty. Also, Skinbark’s game-text will prevent you Hobbits from dying to cards like Hate, Whirling Strike and even just losing a skirmish when they are exhausted. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Threw Down My Enemy – I think this is Decipher’s attempt at making the downside of Bunyan Gandalf somewhat of a good thing. It is not very successful. Combined with Shadowfax, It becomes a decent pumper for Gandalf, but suffers from the same problem as every other Gandalf pumper….it’s not as good as Servant. It just does not pay to play a card that pumps only Gandalf when you can use a card that does the same thing, but works on everyone. Berserkers beware, though.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Treebeard, Guardian of the Forest – ahhh, the biggest headache card in the set. This guy goes in every Ent deck, right? I mean, how can you pass up a 12 Strength, 4 vitality companion who can make your ents damage +1? Well, it seems that it would be a lot better to use the ally(either version, but probably the common) so that all of your Ent companions cost a lot less. Also, the 2 extra strength is really not that needed, when you have pumpers like Ent Moot and Enraged. Also, having to exert an unbound Hobbit to let him fight is a lot rougher than you’d think.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Smeagol/ Gollum – there are some very good cards in this lot. Some of the cards in here are going to make opponents wary of playing small minions, while others are going to make Gollum a monster.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Don’t Follow the Lights – alright, this ones not great. First off smeagol has to win a fight. While this might not be a problem against shadows like Moria or Sauron, it’ll be a dead card in your hand against bigger cultures, like Nagul and Warg-Riders. Luckily, you can use Don’t Look at Them to pitch these useless ones and take out the Nazgul while you’re at it. A sub-par card.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Don’t Look at Them – a cycling machine and cleanup for Smeagol. Quite good against Dunland and Moria to stop the whole stacking on Swarms thing that becomes a big problem with Smeagol. This combined with Slinker means that as long as you want him around, Smeagol ain;t going nowhere. Beware the Palantir.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Not Listening – this card suffers from the same drawbacks as Don’t Follow the Lights, but has a lesser payoff, meaning it is a less widely usable card. The biggest possibitly I can find here is pumping Slinker twice with burdens and then removing them with this card. Like I said, not so great.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Safe Paths – well, here comes the headaches. This is obviously a game winner, but can also be a game loser if played at the wrong time. This ones a lot easier to use than the gollum counterpart, though it’s not quite as overwhelming when it’s pulled off. Should be quite easy to keep Smeagol unwounded, assuming you’re using Slinker. The complicated part is being able to survive a triple move when you’re giving your opponent 5 free pool and whichever 3 cards they feel are going to murder you best. On the one hand, I have been in situations with HiDaN decks where I felt I could have easily moved 3 times, same with Trust decks. The problem here is the number of cultures involved in incorporating Smeagol into these builds. This card will see little play, INMHO.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Smeagol, Poor Creature – now heres a stud if I’ve ever seen one. Better at cycling than any card ever printed, and able to stay alive as long as you’re willing to give up some cardboard. Semagol, PC is the ultimate patsy as he’ll stick around until you stop feeding him and then take one for the team. While he may not be winning skirmishes, PC will be a great speedbump on the way to 3. I forsee a great future in this little fella’s destiny, or something. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Gollum, OV – on the other hand, this guy is not nearly as good as his rare cousin from BOHD. While being able to cycle is good, it is much easier to playa permanent on the fellowship side to achieve the same effect with more consistency. Since you will always have to pitch cards to make this guy win fights, he gets the cold shoulder. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Master Broke His Promise – even worse than Safe Paths, this is the card you will NEVER play. Sure, if you DO manage to play one these it can win the game, but being that there is no form of wound prevention or healing for Gollum, and the Free Peoples get the first regroup action, this card will be nigh impossible to play. Rohan shuts it down hardcore, since one horse stops it. Elves stop it thanks to Greenleaf. Gondor can DiaH, Fortify and Aragorn’s Bow him. Basically, the only Free Peoples that will get this card played on it is Hobbits, and that’ll be tough because of the choke that’ll almost definitely accompany the Hobbits. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Nasty, Foul Hobbitses – now heres a good one. This card, combined with Stinker, means every time Gollum wins he gets +2 strength. That’s just plain huge. In a burden deck, this card will be your best friend. Simply wait to play Gollum AFTER you’re loaded up the burdens, and you’re almost guaranteed to win every fight afterwards. While it’s vulnerable to Gollum not winning, it does not suffer from the weaknesses of MBHP since you need no exertions. Good for burdens, useless otherwise.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
They Stole It – the other side on Don’t Look at Them, again Gollum gets the short end of the stick. Wounding a companion fighting Golum for three cards would be better if Gollum was more likely to win fights. As it stands, it does make it easier to decide who can and cannot fight Gollum, and it provides a much better Shadow cycling option than Old Villain. The wound Hobbits Twice is really quite nice, assuming you can get the opponent to assign to a Hobbit with this card on the table. The downside is that to really use this card effectively, you’re going to be playing at the most 2 Shadow cards. That’s bad.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
You’re a Liar and a Thief – a response speed Hate for Gollum. Again, the problem of Gollum winning a skirmish. The best way for Gollum to win skirmishes is to add burdens, and this card, while really quite good in theory, will only be regularly playable in a corruption deck. In that case, you’d be better off just playing Nasty Foul Hobbitses and finish the job you started with the burdens. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Gondor – an interesting variety of cards this time around for Gondor. We get help for RBRangers, a whole new multi-culture Aragorn strategy and a stupid Banner. Also, even though Decipher promised us help for the Knights, all we get is another fortification, and this one is weaker than all the first 3.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Anborn, Skilled Huntsman – this fella ain’t bad. The fact that Ancient Roads all but eliminates the need for Gondorian Rangers means there’s more room for side-show guys like Anborn. Unfortunately, if theres a minion that needs it’s site number modified to be roaming, in all likelihood ALL the minions need it, making the chances of Anborn winning a fight slim. Basically, if his game-text is kicking in, it’s not really needed. I think he’ll see little play outside of sealed and draft.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Ancient Roads – now this is a cool card. No longer do you need to tote around those useless little Gondorian Rangers just so minions stay Roaming, all you need is 3 Rangers and Ancient Roads and you’ve got a bunch of minions out of place. The downside is, of course, that it’s a condtion. Basically, you eliminate the need to tempt Enquea in favor of tempting Saruman’s Power and Wild Man Raid. Pick your poison.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Aragorn, Defender of Free Peoples – there was a lot of speculation about what Aragorn would do. Hopes were high, and frankly I was initially disappointed. Now that I think about him a bit more, I feel that Aragorn is quite good. While you will need to tempt Chief Counselor(not to mention all the other culture cards) to get the most bang out of your buck, the biggest strength Aragorn has is combined with a fighting Elf deck. Strength of Arms will provide you with tokens when your Elves win, and Aragorn will win fights thanks to those tokens. The Dwarf abilty is not really worth using Dwarves, since Gimli has access to enough healing if he wants it. The Rohan ability is decent, but falls short thanks to the requirement of Aragorn being mounted. While not wuite as powerful as some had hoped, Aragorn, DOFP is a great card, and a good replacement for Heir to the White City in Last Alliance decks. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Banner of Westernesse – ugh, stupid Banners. Again, I reiterate the idiocy of making a Hand Weapon that gives no strength bonus but has a special ability that triggers when the bearer wins a skirmish. Ugh. The healing is alright, and the liberation is good, but both are easily found in other cards that are easier to play. Athelas? Forests of Ithilien?<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Faramir, Ithilien Ranger – I guess it was a good idea to make a Faramir that could start for 2 without playing Ringbound Rangers. Unfortunately, he will never see play in non-ringbound decks because Son of Denethor is so good. Also, his gametext(basically allowing you to pitch a copy of a non-unique ranger to heal one) works only for ringbound decks. Captain of Gondor is much better for Ringbound decks because of his extra 2 strength, which can make a huge difference. Ithilien Ranger suffers from the same syndrome as Arwen, EOHP simply because her other version(s) are much better.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Garrison of Osgiliath – this is what we get as a helper card for the Knights. Ugh. About the same as the elven condition agility, it’s a pumper that you can use as much or as little as you need. The only up side is that it’s a fortification, so you can play it back with Take Cover, so it’s not all bad. Unfortunately, it’s nothing like what the Knights really needed, which is some form of Fortification protection, somewhat like Siege Engine. Oh well.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Mortal Men – a new twist on Gondor pumps. Usually gondor pumps give +2 and them + more if something special is happening. This is actually a great card with Eomer, TM since it’ll be a +2 pump for Aragorn(or whoever) and then a permanent +2 for Eomer as long as he’s fighting the minion you exert. Not a great card, but useful.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Perilous Ventures – well, I guess this is the Nazgul protection in Towers block, but I don’t see it getting played a whole lot in Standard. Gondor’s Vengeance does exactly the same thing with only one exertion, are you willing to play a sub-par card just on the off chance that your opponent is playing Nazgul? I didn’t think so.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Rig of Barahir – alright, big deal made over this card by Decipher, but I don’t see it. First of all, it’s a card that plays on Aragorn and it does nothing for him. In an Elf deck, I’d rather use the 2 Grima-Safe slots for Ranger;s Sword and a Last Alliance. In a Rohan deck, I’d rather Ranger;s Sword and Aragorn’s Bow, or even a horse. In a Dwarf deck….well I’ll leave that to you. Not a bad card, but weak thanks to the existence of Wortongue. Now if only they’d make a card that made Aragorn un-Grimable.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Trust – well now we have two things we could mean when we’re playing a Trust deck J<br />
Another example of a gondor pump, but you get some healing if elves are doing alright. This is decent, but not quite as good as Mortal Men. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Isengard – Decipher has again puzzled me. Why make a cool card like Agents of Orthanc, not to mention the other great cards that trigger off of multiple cultures, when you are going to almost kill rainbow decks with chief counselor? The Isengard Men have some potential, especially Desertion + Bill Ferny(think about it), but they seem to be missing something. I am sure they’ll be matched up with other cultures to great effect.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Agents of Orthanc – like I said in the intro, it baffles me that Decipher would make a card like this one expansion after they made a card that nukes rainbow decks single-handedly. As it stands, this guy is going to be almost always an 11 damage +1 for 5 pool. Not bad, but still not great. Heaven forbid your opponent stuck to 2 cultures, then you get to pay 5 for a 9 with no ability. I imagine this guy with be essential in an Isen Man deck, but I doubt he’ll be played otherwise.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
 <br />
Assault Ladder – so this is basically a worse Saruman;s Ambition. The good is that it can be protected by Siege Engine, unlike Saruman’s Ambition, and it pumps by 3. The bad is that it costs 1 and you’ll need to dedicate some Uruks to loading it. I would imagine you’ll see it in some Berserker decks, but it’s unlikely to be played anywhere else.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Banner of Isengard – perhaps the best of the Banners, which isn’t saying much. For one, theres a strength bonus here. Secondly, the effect is quite astounding in a Site Control deck. The other interesting thing to mention here is that the Banner can be given to any of the Isengard Men, meaning you can boost Grima to Frodo beating range. Site Control is hard to set up for Isengard currently, but I could see this being quite effective in a Warg Site Control deck giving a purpose to those sites even if Wolves of Isengard gets discarded.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Berserk Butcher -   alright, this guy is sweet. Granted, one Defend it and Hope and he does nothing, but if he has a Broad Bladed Sword then it’s like all your Uruks have ‘em. He’ll definitely show up in multiples in Machine decks as an alternative to the Rager and the plain old Berserker, who I have NEVER seen played outside of Draft. Yes, expensive, but a great ability on a big minion that is a rare = a desirable card.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Desertion – sure to be a core card in the new IsenMen strategies. Send Unferth at Aragorn and then add Bill Ferny to watch the opponent’s weapons go bye bye(twisted tales). While weak to condition removal(like all conditions, duh :P ) the minus 1 strength alone is pretty cool. Definitely an important card.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Fires and Foul Fumes – alright, heres the deal. This card is tempting, right? Cause there’s lots of ways to make sure you have the 4 pool, what with all the new orcs that discard to add pool, and the ability to wound a companion 4 times(basically, to kill him) is neatto! Whats the big problem? Why isn’t this card, ahem, broken? Cause it sucks, that’s why! How many times are you going to get 4 Orcs to the regroup phase, while you have the setup to add the pool(or have it saved) and have it really make a difference? I mean, c’mon, if you’ve got 4 pool left and 4 IsenOrcs in the regroup, doesn’t that mean that you’re already winning the game? Haven’t you obviously got the fellowship on the ropes to the point that wounding a companion 4 times will make little to no difference? This card seems cool at first, but falls short just like Safe Paths, MBHP and all the other so called “laugh out loud” cards. I’m not laughing.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Gnawing, Biting, Hacking Burning – ahhh! A very good card…maybe. Recursion is always a plus, and the fact that there’s no other real way to get back Isen Orcs in Standard, and you’ve got a card that’s good for lack of a better candidate. The down side is that you have to use a regroup action to discard them, which means you’ll have to play a good number of the new Orcs, AND the one’s on GBHB are not the ones getting replayed. I imagine this will be huge in Sealed and Draft.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Iron Fist of the Orc – potential here, but it’s going to take way too long to get set up for the possession removal to have much effect. A fast moving fellowship will get too far along the site path for this card to get set up before one or two possession losses will hurt them, and slower moving fellowships really don’t rely on possessions. Plus side? A way for Isen Orcs to deal with that stupid Frying Pan.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Isengard Artisan – alright, I’ll go ahead and say everything I need to about this variety of minion in this spot. This is a needed addition to the Isen Orcs “menu”. Between these Orcs and the old Orcs, you’ll get 4 wounds(ideally) from each Isen Orc that makes it to the regroup. Also, they don’t need vitality in themselves to cause damage to the fellowship, so combined with Trapped and Alone they will almost always make it to the regroup phase(even a mounted Eomer only does 2 wounds) alive, which means a wound. The down side is that that wound is almost the same as them winning the skirmish…except they get discarded, making a large fellowship(or even a small one with healing) able to double move with little problems. Honestly, I think that the Mechanics are the only card needed to make the Isen Orcs at least slightly viable, since they cause multiple wounds per minion, giving a better deal, somewhat making up for the discard of the minion. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Isengard Builder – hmmm, seems pretty stupid to me. The only purpose that arises in my mind is twilight to feed the Tender, who has his own problems, but I’ll get there. I know that extra pool often discourages the double move, but it occurs to me that there are better uses for Isen Orcs stacked on a hand card than adding 2 pool. I may be missing something here, but I honestly doubt it. Anyone? J<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Isengard Journeyman – see Artisan<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Isengard Mechanics – no heres the beauty. This fellow will see much play in Isen Orc decks, and might even sneak on over to some other. He is truly the best crowd control in Towers Block. Unfortunately, he is going to usually require a heavy dedication to Isen Orcs. A smart Free Peoples player will kill down to 5 before this guy cleans house, but sometimes that won’t be possible. Big minion + awesome text + stupid second hand ability = star of Isen Orcs. Whether or not Isen Orcs end up popular(which they could), this guy will be the lynchpin.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Isengard Plodder – see Artisan<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Isengard Tender – this is an example of good meat on a bad bun. The game text of the Tender is game-breaking. He can cripple a fellowship in seconds, combined with the Orcs that add pool or just saving pool, multiple companions can be exhausted by multiple Tenders, setting up the opponent for a massacre at the next site. The big problem is his small stature. He is easily overwhelmed by almost any companion with a Hand weapon, which means that losing Damage bonuses from weapons does not matter. The other down side will be that his 2 vitality makes him VERY vulnerable to horses, since they won’t need damage bonuses to do the 2 wounds to off him. Isengard Shaman can keep him alive from wounds, but can’t anything about him being overwhelmed. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Isengard Tinker – ummm, see Artisan.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Rohirrim Traitor – ahhh, pretty cool. The potential of this is quite good, since it will almost always be an 8. Combined with Unferth, you have an semi-swarm feel, especially since they stop roaming at 3. Will see play in Isen Men decks, but not much else. Since the Isen Men have no wound prevention, they will be VERY vulnerable to archery and wounding(like DiaH and Ranger’s Bow), so that 2 vitality will be a problem. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Scaffolding – potential, but alas there are better wound preventers and better still cards to stack your Orcs on. If you want to prevent wounds, go with Isengard Shaman. He costs the same and doesn’t take any time to set up. In Isen Orc decks without other stackers, this will see play simply because of no better way to use those discarded guys.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Sharku, Vile Marauder – another one of the pool adding guys, and one who has a much better version already in print. Why would I want to use this guy, ever? I just can’t think of a reason. If he is supposed to work with Isen Orc decks, why wouldn’t you want to use the other one that’ll cause at least 1 wound(assuming you play a Warg on him) when this one on his own Warg will, if he wins both fights, get to add 5 pool and be exhausted, losing his fierceness and making him highly vulnerable to Eomer and every wound card on the planet? I am lost. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Twisted Tales – the most tempting card about the Isen Men. Stackable War Clubs sounds pretty NOICE, especially when the weapon stays on the table so they can’t Ecglaf it, or Weapon Store or whatever. Also, just in case someone plays Elven Brooch, Twisted Tales is immune to it! Getting the Isen Men to win a skirmish is another problem, but I don’t mind pointing out the Desertion/ Bill Ferny combo again. Really, a very good card. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Durin’s Tower – well, I’ll start off by saying that the cost reduction at 2T and 3T is almost redundant. If you have enough pool to play the Balrog at either of those sites, and have the condtion and have the Balrog, then you’re a darn lucky dude and I never wanna play you in a game. That aside, I still see this seeing some play as it is a portable Moria pump, and the first one for the Troll or the Rog. Since it’s free and has some utility, I would never leave out that one card slot that might make the difference between the Troll overwhelming someone or not. Don’t forget, it can pump Guard Commander and Keyward. Not bad.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
The Balrog, Terror of Flame and Shadow – expensive? Yes. Cool looking? Yes. Monstrous? Yes. Playable? Yes and no. The best thing about the Fellowship Balrog(s) was that they were guaranteed at site 5. I mean, if all else failed, you had the Rog to fall back on to cause some damage. Unfortunately, we’ll never have the TOFAS at the Bridge, which is a pity since he would absolutely rock. As it stands, the cheapest we’ll ever get the Balrog in play is with 10 pool(assuming you have a runner. You do have a runner don’t you?). While 10 pool does not seem like a lot, think about what you COULD have for 10 pool. The Balrog will cause, at most, one death. For 11 Twilight(and a moria minion) you get one dead companion, or less. You will most likely get a stop, but you may not. If the opponent is doubling into 9, they won’t care at all about the Rog since he usually won’t be able to fight Frodo(most people are playing the Pan these days) so they can actually leave him unassigned. He will NOT make it into Moria Swarm decks, at least not dedicated swarm decks. He will, on the other hand, make it possible for Moria decks to be stoppers. Imagine this guy combined with a Troll(and a Durin’s Tower on the table) or two! If TOFAS gets a lot of play, expect both armor and Boromir, LoG do return to the scene. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Raider – the raider cultures gets quite a boost, especially considering the few cards they received this set. Wound prevention is huge for Easterlings, some recursion for Southrons etc. Good lot here.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Easterling Army – another big fierce minion for the Easterlings means you need no longer depend on multiple Captains for stopping power. Also, the fact that these guys are non-unique is pretty cool. 6 pool for a 13 fierce is nice, and the pump power is just icing on the cake. I really look forward to playing with this guy, and Army + Vision From Afar = burden.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Easterling Polearm – huge. So important. A culture is NOT complete until it has some form of wound prevention. The biggest problem with Easterlings has been that the burden adders can be DiaH’ed, archeried and anything else. 2 Burdens is usually wuite easy to get, and once you do they’ll have to assign to Ringbound to prevent burdens. The fact that once you hit 5 burdens, which is the kill level for a burden deck, you get a bonus Damage +1. I would think that a Captain or Army with a Polearm will be an auto stop for most fellowships, as long as there are 2 burdens. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Southron Archer Legion – interesting here. It seems Decipher wants Southron Archery to  <br />
Be a viable strategy on it’s own. Not only is this fellow a large minion, but he is an archer and a multi archer. For 8 pool, you slap this guy down. 2 more for a Mumak. Then, assuming the opponent has 5 companions which is the regular) every 3 pool(up to 12) = another wound for the opponent. He is quite expensive, but does not really need any support to hurt the fellowship. Potential here, but not the card that is going to make the Southrons win a tournament. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Southron Invaders – this card on the other hand, is a bigger step in the right direction. The ability to grab any southron with ambush(with includes some of the best, though unfortunately not Desert Lord) when you play him. This means that all you need is one invader and another Southron to pull out 4 Invaders and any other ambusher from dicard. They are quite expensive, and rightly so as a cheaper version of this guy could be ridiculous. A good, balanced card that will see play, assuming Southrons see play at all.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Trample – I am at a loss as the need for this card to be made. Flanking attack seems to do the exact same thing, except without you opponent being able to stop it by discarding a guy. Would be loads better in the shadow phase, but then it’d be possible broken. I guess saving the exertion over Flanking Attack is sometimes worth it, and yes, usually your opponent is going to let you add the pool, butall in all it looks like just another dissapointment rare. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Fell Beast – ahhh, the flagship card of the set. A good addition to the Nazgul arsenal, as it provides some much needed cycling and an easy way to make Twilight Nazgul fierce. Unfortunately, that discard cost isn’t always going to be easy to pay and Twilight Nazgul are pretty weak all arounf. They get a boost, a big one, in this set but the fact that they are still inherently weak is a testament to their initially poor powers. The fact that it’s a mount hurts too, as Black Steed is a staple of most Nazgul decks currently and most people would rather have a Steed than a Beast any day. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Spied From Above – an attempt at giving the Nazgul some form of late game stopping power, something they have been missing forever. With Filbert and OEG gone from Standard, the Nazgul were thought to have the endurance they were lacking, but alas it is found that once fellowships get set up it becomes increasingly hard to overwhelm, much less kill, a companion with Nazgul. I don’t see how wounding a Nazgul twice and playing another one exhausted is going to stop a fellowship that would have moved on a healthy Nazgul, but I know there are uses. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Sword of Dol Guldur – is this Toldea’s set, or what? He gets a new, more widely playable,version and a sword that caused no small uproar when it’s text was released. I doubt this’ll see much play unless Toldea is deemed a better card that Cantea(or Attea), but the effect of screwing conditions and possessions is indeed a tough one. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
The Witch King, Deathless Lord – alright, this card sucks. I am glad theres a version of the King that everyone can easily get their hands on now, but this version might as well have NO gametext. Yes, sometimes he will kill a companion or two when played in the early game, but how many times are those extra exertions(much less the ally wounding) going to matter if you are already killing companions? Yes, he discourages feeding disposable companions and such to Nazgul, but if you want to do that play with Drawn to it’s power. Another victim of better versions already around.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Ulaire Lemenya, Winged Hunter – much potential for abuse, yet still not really all that good. If this guy makes it to the regroup, then yes, he will rock your opponent. Yes, he can win some fights with Ferny’s help, or some Steedage. But he is quite simply too vulnerable to wounds and archery, not to mention mounts, to dedicate a strategy to him. The old much-maligned version of Lemenya is actually more usable. The only way to make him work will be the pull off Not Easily Destroyed with a ton of pool left over. And then you are relying on one condtion.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Ulaire Nertea, Winged Hunter – whats with the repeated subtitles, huh? Great picture here, by the way. Just like the agents of Orthanc, he suffers because of the harshness of Grima, Chief Counselor. This guy would punish Rainbow fellowships enough that they would be seen less, but as it stands he’ll usually cause an exertion when he comes into play, which is easily assigned to Frodo, or anyone else. Band Grima, and watch Winged Hunter shine.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Ulaire Toldea, Winged Sentry – why is it that the two wimpy guys are the Hunters, and the bigger fierce guy gets stuck with sentry duty? He’s even got his own sword! Much more powerful than his first version simply because his game text will be triggered a lot more often. A good card, and it will see much play. In fact, I wouldn’t be too surprised if people played him so much that no one worried about Oldea anymore. See how I made a pun?<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Winged and Ominous – a pretty good card to draw up early. The Nazgul are strong in the early game, and they will almost always have the vitality to store up some juice for later. This will lead to more Nazgul hitting the table later on, meaning more of them to power this card. If not drawn early enough, you’ll find yourself struggling for vitality to power the condtion, or wondering if it might be better to save the wounds in case the opponent moves twice. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Rohan – ahh, my favorite culture gets a couple of really cool cards this et, but doesn’t make any leaps and bound. I am not disappointed with Eomer.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Banner of the Mark – another stupid Banner, and one that is quite stupid. Nuff said. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Blood has Been Spilled – ah! Interesting idea, although probably unneeded. I don’t think I’ve ever seen a mounted man be overwhelmed by anything, but I guess there’s a first time for everything. I guess if the bigger minions become the norm, we’ll see more of this card. I doubt it.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Eomer, Rohirrim Captain – I was worried what they would do to this Eomer. Obviously, he wasn’t going to be the same as Third Marshal, and there’s no way he’d be better. I think they did it just right. Making him valiant means I can leave Theoden out of my decks and still use Let Us Be Swift, and his gametext means that ANY Rohan Man can win a fight if a want him to, bestowing Eomer-like traits upon them for 3 cards. This is good for cycling as well as skirmishing. Simply awesome.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Ever the Hope of Men – ummm, no. If you didn’t kill them in the first place, your Free Peoples are in no shape to double time, and if your in no shape to double time, adding two more wounds to clear out 2 wounded minions isn’t helping enough. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Hama, Doorward of Theoden – he’s a big joke, right? Ahh, but he deals with War Clubs better than any Rohan card yet, short of maybe Arrow Slits, which can be discarded. Unfortunately, he isn’t going to be stealing any Wargs anytime soon, but everything else is fair game. A very good sacrificial lamb and a better rare than many I’ve already talked about.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Hrethel, Rider of Rohan – interesting twist on Eomer here. For the price of negating the wound your mount caused, this guy gets bigger than Eomer. He’ll have to have a Rider’s Spear to get around that, but he has the potential to replace an Elite Rider in some Rohan decks. I know I’ll give him a try. Not good against Nazgul, since winning the first fight won’t kill them, but great against 2 vitality cultures like Uruks and maybe Raiders. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
News From the Mark – another card that begs to be pulled off, but probably never will. The potential to move 4 sites in one turn in very nice, but how often is it going to happen? Especially when your opponent gets to draw those 6 cards to use against you. Creates some interesting thinking for you opponent, since they don’t know if you’ll stop or really try to move, so those 6 cards might go to waste. All in all, the best move limit upper that we have right now, unfortunately that’s not saying much.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
We Left None Alive – ah, now this is quite good. A “stackable” pumper that is better than average. This condition is especially good against Dunland, which is important  since they are Rohan’s worst matchup. Not much to say here, this’ll be seen in lots of decks.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Sauron – my girlfriend is stoked about the Trolls, and I won’t lie, so am I. I have always been left with a headache trying to make Sauron work, and this set is no exception. A few standout cards hide in amongst more cards that are just “okay”.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Banner of the Eye – probably second best Banner, but again, the Banners all pretty much make love to Anna Nicole Smith. Sauron has no way to use extra pool in the skirmish phase, and only one way to use the extra in regroup(Teeth). Another attempt at making a reason for Sauron Site control, but a bad one. Gimme a Vile Blade any day.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Corpse Lights – the twilight minions are interesting, in that they try to separate themselves from the Orcs and really ally with the Nazgul. Providing a minion based pumper for both the Dead Dudes and Twilight Nazgul, Corpse Lights is kinda cool. Shut down by Rohan, but kinda cool. That is all.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Dead Ones – really strange that these guys are Damage +1, especially since they all but eliminated them from swarm decks with the to play restriction. I guess the power here would be to get out several of these guys and a Corpse Lights and pump one of them to win. But that would be stupid. The low vitality and lack of wound prevention makes this minion even worse than you thought. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Gate Picket – ahh, another victim of Chief Counselor. Unfortunately, even in the Grima’s absence this would be a bad card. Since the Free Peoples player chooses the cultures, they can just let their Hobbits take wounds and prevent everyone else from the pain. Also, most rainbow decks will have mostly disposable companions and few allies, meaning that they can afford to take the wounds from this guy. I know I am gonna pull a ton of this guy.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Gate Sentry – hmmm, take an Orc Patrol and remove the Tracker text and make him smaller, and you have this guy. Up side would be that Sentry is not unique, so you can nuke multiple condtions. I just feel like there are better Orcs to play in his stead. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Gate Troll – ahhh, the Trolls. They are just really neat. Not overly expensive, no need to spot a Sauron Orc and fierce. Gets bigger when played with Sauron, but I honestly feel like he’ll see the table more often in a Moria Troll deck. Underground, the Troll comes down for 5 with the Keyward, followed by Gate Troll for 4. Just really cool. I nice boost for Sauron decks, but unfortunately, they WILL stay roaming forever, but 2 extra pool isn’t so bad on a big minion. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Orc Insurgent – now heres a culture enforcer that will see LOTS of play. Most free peoples decks run at least 3 cultures, while some brave the Counselor and play more. This guy will do more in a Moria deck to penalize multi-culture than anything else. He pays for himself in drawing and pool, just amazingly good, and yet not overpowered. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Peril – the better of the two regroup minion players, this is the easiest way for Sauron to control sites. Forget the Fighters, just hold an Infantry and drop in the regroup to grab a site your opponent can’t do anything about. Peril provides the condition to spot and the means to play the Infantry. Now Sauron just needs a reason other than Orc Captain to control a site. Also good with Wisp of Pale Sheen.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Troll of Udun – the bigger, and yet less playable, Troll of the new pair. Still a beast and geared up to overwhelm anyone you want to, most of the time he’s going to cost more than the Balrog. Cycling for Sauron is nice, though somewhat limited by his cost and the discarded card having to be Sauron, he is still a chunky, hard to kill minion.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Troll’s Chain – what? A Troll’s Scimitar? I guess it’s an attempt to make people build Troll decks, but with way to recur them and the Trolls being roaming most of the game, it’ll be hard to play multiple copies, even in a deck running 6 Trolls. Provides a little card drawing for Sauron, but not in the kind of deck where card drawing was needed.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Wisp of Pale (Charlie)Sheen – the best of the new Twilight minions, combined with Peril you have an almost guaranteed burden. The fact that he is a decently costed minion means that he gives you options for some swarming in the late game. Not much else to say.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Shire – hobbits get very little this time around, in fact, Held is probably the only one requiring any thought at all. Hmmm.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Held – much debate over this card, but it’s actually quite good. Does good things for all of the rings, but helps ATAR the most. ATAR sucks against archery decks, anyone will tell you, but no longer. As long as you either kill Frodo off by site 8 or can be sure you’ll win fights OR play Sleep Caradhras, you’ve got what is probably the best defense against archery for people wanting to play ATAR. Also, you’ll get at no extra charge a better way for Isulder’s Bane to deal with Twilight Nazgul. I would imagine that most decks will find a use for this card, but not all decks will need to. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
It Burns Us – well, heres a good way to check out your opponent’s hand in Standard format without using Elves or Gandalf! The extra ability is nice, if somewhat random. I guess this makes it possible for Sam/Frodo/Smeagol decks to double move on occasion.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Kept Safe – well, ummm, no. I wonder what Decipher’s paranoia was about the Unbound Hobbits being wounded to death? First Skinbark and now this. I guess at best it’s going to be a way for you to counteract some wounding strategies, and at worst it can serve as uncomfortable toilet paper, along with Store Room and all of the Banners.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Long Slow Wrath – now this has potential. Merry From O’er the Brandywine can be quite a fighter with this card, and the exertion will be worth it to kill off a monster. Most Ent decks are going to have 3 Hobbits and 6 Ents, meaning Merry becomes a 13 and layeth the smacketh down on a Nazgul. Cool. Unfortunately, if you’re playing Hobbits you’re not playing them as fighters, but as support for the Trees. A neat and interesting card, with some potential, but not top tier.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Merry, Impatient Hobbit – okay, this is bad. I thought it was bad when I saw the rare Merry from Towers, but this guy is way worse. You can’t tell me that you’d be willing to sacrifice a companion just to heal one wound off of a companion, even if it was any companion. I guess the best thing about him is that he can almost always be relied upon to be discarded, allowing you to replay him next turn, fresh as a summer’s eve.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Pippin, Hastiest of them All – same as Merry, only possibly worse. Possibly. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Sites – well, whats to say. Some neat new sites to consider. Valley of Saruman is going to be played a lot, though I must say I am sad that they brought back a site from Fellowship. I was kind of hoping we’d get all new sites in every block. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Hornburg Hall – hmm, not particularly useful, but might enable you to build a better shadow hand should you be too far behind to win with the fellowship. Unfortunately(I seem to be saying this a lot) most of the Theoden signet companions are sub-par, with Eomer, TM and Aragorn, DOFP being the exceptions to the rule.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Meduseld – this is quite neat, in that we get the opportunity to play a companion from the dead pile with a site’s text. I pity the deck that needs to use it, though, as it is a site 3 meaning a companion has to have been lost in one or 2 turns at the most.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Rocks of Emyn Muil – interesting, as we get a site that possibly allows us to bid higher in anticipation of drawing into multiple Frodo Signet companions on turn one. Most likely to be relegated to the “harmless” pile of sites, along with Streets of Edoras and Hornburg Wall. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Saruman’s Laboratory – probably the site that’ll see the most use out of this set, short of perhaps Westfold. Being able to pitch cards to stop archery, DiaH, PATHS and even Cliffs is just huge, especially for cultures that lack any wound prevention of their own. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Valley of Saruman – remember Anduin Confluence? It’s BAAAAAACK. Without the horn to make allies fight, the biggest use here will be to nuke Treebeard before he can fight, and there’ll be nothing the fellowship can do about it. Cool for neutering that unbound Hobbit deck that keeps recurring Merry to heal for the Pan, or Pippin to soak up archery and remove Uruks. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
Westfold – dontcha love how Decipher pulled a switcheroo on us between the rulebook of Ents and the actual set? Being able to potentially pull out 2- 4 companions in one turn is making people go nuts fot the possibilities. Unfortunately(theres that word again) the most efficient way to get multiple guys out is going to be NOT starting Aragorn so you get more copies, but then you may not draw him. Starting Aragorn means that unless you get a lucky draw your going to be movin with 3 companions, one of whom is close to death. I site on many possibilities, all of which have potential to be great.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
well, that’s the end of my Ents article. I know I came off as a bit pessimistic on some of the cards, I really feel like it’s a good set overall. Many new things tried, and several good cards both common and rare. Some things that’ll make the game different and more interesting and some that’ll just plain be really good cards. Down sides would be no help for Knights, nothing of interest for Hobbits and we are left with no truly Wizardly Gandalf in Towers Block. <br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
I hope you have been informed, and I hope you learned something. Thanks for taking the time to read this, and I will do my best to respond to any comments made on the article.<br />
<br /><br />
<br /><br />
The Carny<br />
